description.plain:
As a voice of guidance, Woodkid uses “Run Boy Run” to help a boy going through his first stages in life. On the surface, this song is fairly straightforward, warning the boy about struggles he will face and giving him hope to meet them.

However, on the other side of the coin, this song is also likely about being gay, and giving hope to a young man who is just starting to discover that he is gay. On January 19, 2014, Woodkid posted on his Facebook page deriding La Manif Pour Tous, a French anti-gay group, for using this song in one of their videos. In his words,

I JUST CANT STOP LAUGHING. The people from LA MANIF POUR TOUS in Roma are so stupid that they are using the most pro-gay music in their promo. Not sure they got time to read the lyrics.

In addition, Woodkid himself is openly gay.

description.plain:
In an interview with Le Parisien, Woodkid discussed the first single of his sophomore album, S16:

It is a love song that talks about a larger subject, the notion of dominance and being dominated, and the hope that the individual can fight against the great forces. In the coal mine of the clip, we can see lots of things, the smallness of man in the face of the ecological challenge, in the face of the rise of the extreme right in our countries, which terrifies me and makes me angry. Musically, I also needed a track that would transition between the two albums. I’ll pick up where we left off and take you somewhere else, where my sound and my words went.

description.plain:
Ghost Lights begins with a haunting organ overture, then a deep drum beat begins. Woodkid’s haunting voice rises above the increasing instrumentation, with the added instrumentation of a metal-against-metal sound and church bells.
At the chorus, strings begin a sweeping, almost-triumphant movement which, along with the increased percussive tempo, rises the action through the chorus. The return of the verses strips the instrumentation down again, but rebuilds slowly. As we reach the end of this epic score, the pitch rises with the addition of brass. As we almost reach the conclusion, the music suddenly tapers off, leaving the listener intrigued and wanting more.
Truly a stellar and moving work.

description.plain:
Continuing the story presented throughout the album, the boy decides to join in a war after losing his loved one.
In this song, the boy is conflicted with the choice of going to war or not. He’s wondering if his ultimate decision to go to war is something that his loved one would have wanted, but he realizes it’s too late to turn back.

The name of the song is a reference to a Christian hymn about the suffering of Christ’s mother- the Virgin Mary. Stabat Mater Doloroso means ‘the sorrowful mother stood’. This implies that the woman Woodkid refers to in the line ‘do you still braid some flowers in your hair?’ is his mother. His mother is sorrowful as a result of Woodkid’s recruitment into a war, most probably World War One due to the mention of a ‘train’ and ‘horses’. This would make sense as in 1914 at the outbreak of the war many of the youth joined the war effort for fun as they believed it would be over by Christmas ‘do you remember when we thought war was just a game’- however this was entirely wrong and the war continued on for an additional four years claiming millions of lives. The overarching theme of this song is the deceptive nature of war and the devastating effect it can have on the love ones left behind.
